{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20141201163848|636187780","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Martha_Roby","to":"Martha Roby"}],"pages":{"29218153":{"pageid":29218153,"ns":0,"title":"Martha Roby","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2014-12-04T20:30:55Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{Infobox congressman\n|name = Martha Roby\n|image =Martha roby 113 congressional portrait.jpg\n|imagesize= \n|state = [[Alabama]]\n|district = [[Alabama's 2nd congressional district|2nd]]\n|term_start = January 3, 2011\n|preceded = [[Bobby Bright]]\n|succeeded =\n|party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1976|07|26}}\n|birth_place = [[Montgomery, Alabama]], U.S.\n|alma_mater=[[New York University]]<br>[[Samford University]]\n|profession = [[Lawyer]]<br/>[[Politician]]\n|spouse = Riley Roby \n|children = Margaret Roby<br>George Roby\n|residence = [[Montgomery, Alabama]]\n|religion = [[Presbyterian Church (U.S.A.)|Presbyterian]]\n}}\n'''Martha Dubina Roby'''<ref>http://www.legistorm.com/memberbio/2723/Rep_Martha_Roby_AL.html</ref> (born July 26, 1976) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|Alabama|2}}. She is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. She defeated incumbent Representative [[Bobby Bright]] on November 2 during the [[United States House of Representatives elections in Alabama, 2010]],<ref>[http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/article/20101102/NEWS/101102052/GOP+s+Roby+defeats+Bright+in+Alabama+s+2nd+District+ GOP's Roby defeats Bright in Alabama's 2nd District] ''[[Montgomery Advertiser]]'' November 2, 1010</ref> and assumed office in January 2011. Roby and [[Terri Sewell]] are the first women [[United States congressional delegations from Alabama|elected to Congress from Alabama]] in regular elections.<ref>[[Elizabeth B. Andrews]] was elected to fill an unexpired term in the House, while Senators [[Dixie Bibb Graves]] and [[Maryon Pittman Allen]] were appointed and never elected.</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and legal career==\nRoby was born in [[Montgomery, Alabama]] and attended [[New York University]], where she received a [[bachelor of music]] degree. She then entered the [[Cumberland School of Law]] at [[Samford University]] in [[Birmingham, Alabama]], receiving her [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] in 2001.  She is the daughter of [[Joel F. Dubina]], a Senior Judge on the United States Court of Appeals for the Eleventh Circuit.\n\nBefore entering politics, she worked at the law firm of Copeland, Franco.<ref>{{cite news|title=Biographical Information for 2nd Congressional District GOP runoff candidates|work=Associated Press Newswires|date=8 July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Montgomery City Council==\n===Elections===\nRoby was elected to the Montgomery [[City Council]] in 2003, defeating a total of five opponents, and winning 54.88% of the votes cast in her district.<ref>{{cite news|title = Montgomery Republican plans to challenge Bright in 2010|work = The Dothan Eagle|author=Lance Griffin|url=http://www2.dothaneagle.com/news/2009/jun/26/montgomery_republican_plans_to_challenge_bright_in-ar-193229/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.montgomeryal.gov/Modules/ShowDocument.aspx?documentid=29|title=Municipal Election Results-2003}}</ref> \n\n===Tenure===\nIn her first term on the Council, Roby joined 3 other council members and then mayor Bobby Bright in opposing the building of a shopping mall in East Montgomery,<ref>{{cite news|title=Montgomery Alabama Shopping Mall to Go Up Against Protests, Mayor's Advice|work=The Montgomery Advertiser|date=February 19, 2004}}</ref> opposed privatizing the disposal of household garbage,<ref>{{cite news|title=Trash Service Change Opposed|work=The Montgomery Advertiser|author=Sebastian Kitchen|date=March 30, 2005}}</ref> supported a 10 cent cigarette tax increase,<ref>{{cite news|title=Montgomery, Ala., Cigarette Tax Jumps 10 Cents|work=The Montgomery Advertiser|date=May 14, 2004|author=William F. West}}</ref> and argued for a state [[Tax_holiday#Sales_tax_holidays_in_the_United_States|sales tax holiday]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Montgomery, Ala., council's tax idea might go statewide|author=William F. West|date=August 10, 2004|work=Montgomery Advertiser}}</ref> She headed a committee focused on illegal immigration; the committee's goal was to create a law that revoked business licenses for companies that used illegal aliens.<ref>{{cite web|title=the issues|url=http://www.whorunsgov.com/Profiles/Martha_Roby?loadTab=2}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*Immigration committee\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===Elections===\n;2010\n{{further|United States House of Representatives elections in Alabama, 2010#District 2}}\n\nRoby challenged incumbent Democrat U.S. Congressman and former Montgomery Mayor [[Bobby Bright]] in [[Alabama's 2nd congressional district]]. In the four-candidate Republican primary, Roby ranked first with 49% of the vote, barely missing the 50% threshold needed to win the nomination and avoid a run-off. Rick Barber ranked second with 29% of the vote.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=508440</ref> In the run-off election, Roby defeated him 60%-40%.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=653745</ref>\n\nRoby was endorsed by both [[Newt Gingrich]] and [[Sarah Palin]] in the most expensive race in the district's history.<ref name=\"Alabama 2nd District\">{{cite news |url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2010/house/alabama/2 |title=Alabama 2nd District Profile |deadurl=no |accessdate=4 July 2012 |work=The New York Times}}</ref> Martha Roby spent a total of $1,240,275.64 on her 2010 election. Most of her funds came from large individual contributions. Her top contributor was Jim Wilson and Associates, a Montgomery real estate outfit, who contributed $25,300.00.<ref>{{cite web|title=Open Secerets|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/summary.php?cid=N00030768&cycle=2010|accessdate=21 November 2011}}</ref> Roby's top industry contributor was leadership PAC's. They contributed a total of $106,010.<ref name=\"Alabama 2nd District\"/>\n\nRoby defeated Bright 51%-49%, a difference of 4,780 votes. Roby won just 7 of the district's 16 counties: Autauga, Elmore, Covington, Coffee, Geneva, Dale, and Houston counties. Bright won Montgomery County with 59% of the vote.  Ultimately, Roby's margin in heavily Republican Autauga and Elmore counties proved too much for Bright to overcome.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=487756</ref> \n\n;2012\n{{further|United States House of Representatives elections in Alabama, 2012#District 2}}\nThe 2nd had long been a conservative district, and reverted to form as Roby won a second term, defeating Democrat Therese Ford 64%-36%. She won 11 of the district's 15 counties. However, she lost her home county of Montgomery again, 53%-47%.<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=705230</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/article/20120114/NEWS01/201140338/Candidates-qualify-elections|title=Candidates qualify for elections|date=January 14, 2012|accessdate=January 29, 2012|work=[[Montgomery Advertiser]]|first=Sebastian|last=Kitchen}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nRoby identifies herself as a staunch conservative,<ref>{{cite web|title=Martha Roby for Congress|url=http://www.martharoby.com/pages/15/meet-martha}}</ref> who explained \"true conservative values\" thusly: \"I believe in the sanctity of life. I believe in the protection of the second amendment. I believe in small, limited government and lower taxes. I believe that we should live within our means and I believe in the central role of faith and family in our lives.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Blessing|first=Kelly|title=Martha Roby|url=http://www.whorunsgov.com/Profiles/Martha_Roby|publisher=Washington Post}}</ref> Roby is a signer of [[Americans_for_Tax_Reform#Taxpayer_Protection_Pledge|Americans for Tax Reform]]\u2019s [[Taxpayer Protection Pledge]].<ref name =\"ATR\">{{cite web|title=The Taxpayer Protection Pledge Signers 112th Congressional List|url=http://s3.amazonaws.com/atrfiles/files/files/091411-federalpledgesigners.pdf|publisher=Americans for Tax Reform|accessdate=November 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\n'''Regulation reform'''\nIn December 2011, Roby voted in support of H.R. 10, the \"Regulations From the Executive in Need of Scrutiny Act,\" which would have required Congressional approval for any \"major regulations\" issued by the executive branch but, unlike the 1996 [[Congressional Review Act]], would not require the president's signature or override of a probable presidential veto.<ref name=\"wapo111207\">{{cite news |first=Felicia |last=Sonmez |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |title=REINS bill to expand congressional power over executive regulations passed by House |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/2chambers/post/reins-bill-to-expand-congressional-power-over-executive-regulations-passed-by-house/2011/12/07/gIQAs6VMdO_blog.html |date=December 7, 2011 |accessdate=October 10, 2013}}</ref>\n\n'''Immigration'''\nRoby is an opponent of \"amnesty\" policy for immigrants, and said in a 2010 debate, \"I will never support any legislation with the word 'amnesty' in it.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Blessing |first=Kelly |title=The Issues |url=http://www.whorunsgov.com/Profiles/Martha_Roby?loadTab=2 |accessdate=21 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n'''Abortion'''\nRoby voted \"yea\" for bill HR 358 and HR 3, both bills prohibiting taxpayer money from paying for individual abortions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vote smart|url=http://www.votesmart.org/candidate/key-votes/71604/martha-roby/2/abortion-issues}}</ref> Representative Roby introduced HConRes36, whose purpose was to stop tax payer subsidies from going to [[Planned Parenthood]] which is a multi-million dollar private corporation. Roby believes \"The more taxpayer dollars awarded to Planned Parenthood, the more abortions the group will perform\".<ref>{{cite journal |last=Roby |first=Martha |author2=Diane Black |title=Press release |date=April 12, 2011  |url=http://www.votesmart.org/public-statement/604922/black-roby-introduce-bill-to-defund-planned-parenthood-in-continuing-resolution}}</ref> \n\n'''Agriculture'''\nRoby is a member of the subcommittee for agriculture, energy, and forestry, and believes that federal agencies need to be \"reign[ed] in\".<!--We could 'sic' this but it's pedantic. It is funny, though, if you read the whole quote--><ref>{{cite web|title=agriculture bill|url=http://www.votesmart.org/public-statement/588655/ag-committee-republicans-stress-the-negative-impact-of-federal-regs-on-production-agriculture-rural-economies}}</ref> She believes that the [[Conservation Reserve Program]] (CRP) should be limited.<ref>{{cite web|last=Griffin|first=Lance|title=CRP|url=http://www2.dothaneagle.com/news/2011/nov/16/roby-bill-will-impact-conservation-reserve-program-ar-2713830/|accessdate=21 November 2011}}</ref> Roby believes CRP is causing a loss of farming production. She has also stated that CRP is no longer helping the environment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.votesmart.org/public-statement/623727/roby-brings-alabama-farmers-concerns-to-farm-bill-hearing |title=Roby Brings Alabama Farmers' Concerns to Farm Bill Hearing |deadurl=no |accessdate=4 July 2012}}</ref> She also has spoken out against many of the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|Environmental Protection Agency]] actions, specifically the MACT ruling.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.votesmart.org/public-statement/588655/ag-committee-republicans-stress-the-negative-impact-of-federal-regs-on-production-agriculture-rural-economies |title=Ag Committee Republicans Stress the Negative Impact of Federal Regs on Production Agriculture & Rural Economies |deadurl=no |accessdate=4 July 2012}}</ref> \n\n'''Health care reform'''\nRoby is against government paid-for or sponsored healthcare. She has repeatedly voted to repeal the health care bill also known as the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Votes|url=http://www.votesmart.org/candidate/key-votes/71604/martha-roby/38/health-issues|accessdate=21 November 2011}}</ref> She also voted for the Ryan Budget Bill, which would change medicare into a voucher system.<ref>{{cite web |title=Martha Roby and health care reform |url=http://www.healthreformvotes.org/congress/412394 |accessdate=21 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n'''Defense'''\nRepresentative Roby has consistently voted to prevent any defense spending cuts. She has also voted against a reduction in Navy and Aircraft Procurement<ref>{{cite web|title=bill|url=http://www.votesmart.org/bill/12793/33699/71604/reducing-navy-and-air-force-aircraft-procurement}}</ref> as well as voting \"yea\" for various extension of the armed forces budgets. She has only focused on cutting \"non-defense\" spending.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://roby.house.gov/issue/spending-cuts-and-debt |title=Spending Cuts and Debt |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110106201447/http://roby.house.gov/issue/spending-cuts-and-debt |archivedate=2011-01-06 |accessdate=4 July 2012}}</ref> \n\n'''War in Afghanistan'''\nRoby voted \"Nay\" to remove American forces from Afghanistan by December 31, 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.votesmart.org/bill/12940/34091/71604/removing-troops-from-afghanistan |title=H Con Res 28 - Removing Troops from Afghanistan - Key Vote |deadurl=no |accessdate=4 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n'''Food stamps'''\nRoby voted in September 2013 to cut $39 billion from the food stamp program; the ''[[Montgomery Advertiser]]'' noted that \"About 41,000 households in Roby's southeastern congressional district received food stamps in 2011\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=2013309200025&nclick_check=1|title=House cuts $39B in food stamps; Alabama delegation split on vote|date=20 September 2013|work=[[Montgomery Advertiser]]|accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n'''Taxes'''\nIn 2010 Roby signed a pledge sponsored by [[Americans for Prosperity]] to not vote for any Global Warming legislation that would raise taxes.<ref>http://americansforprosperity.org/noclimatetax//wp-content/uploads/2010/02/roby2.pdf</ref>\n\n===Legislation===\nRoby has sponsored six bills of her own, including:<ref>{{cite web|title=Representative Roby's Legislation|url=http://www.congress.gov/member/martha-roby/1986?q=%7B%22sponsorship%22%3A%22sponsored%22%2C%22type%22%3A%22bills%22%7D|publisher=Library of Congress|accessdate=December 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====112th Congress (2011-2012)====\n* H.R. 3454, a bill to place a cap on acreage included in the [[Conservation Reserve Program]], introduced November 17, 2011, reintroduced in the 113th Congress as H.R. 349\n\n====113th Congress (2013-2014)====\n* H.R. 1406, a bill to require employers to provide their employees with 1.5 hours of [[paid time off]] for each hour of overtime put in by the employee, up to a maximum of 160 hours of paid time off per calendar year, and to require employers to provide monetary compensation to employees after each calendar year for any unused paid time off, introduced April 9, 2013. H.R. 1406 has passed the House of Representatives but has yet to become law.\n\n* H.R. 2089, a bill to prohibit the Department of Education from providing incentives or coercing States to participate in voluntary partnerships with other states to develop and implement shared academic content, standards, and assessments, introduced May 22, 2013\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Conservation, Energy, and Forestry|Subcommittee on Conservation, Energy, and Forestry]]\n**[[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management|Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]'''\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces|Subcommittee on Tactical Air and Land Forces]]\n**[[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Readiness|Subcommittee on Readiness]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|Committee on Education and the Workforce]]'''\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education|Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education]]\n**[[United States House Education Subcommittee on Health, Employment, Labor, and Pensions|Subcommittee on Health, Employment, Labor, and Pensions]]\n*[[ House Select Committee on the Events Surrounding the 2012 Terrorist Attack in Benghazi]]\n*[[Republican Study Committee]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://roby.house.gov/ Congresswoman Martha Roby] official U.S. House site\n*[http://www.martharoby.com/ Martha Roby for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Alabama/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Martha_Roby_%5BR-2%5D}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio = R000591 | ballot = Martha_Roby | nndb = 900/000266102 | votesmart = 71604 | govtrack = 412394 | opencong = 412394 | rollcall = 31387 | politifact = | fec = H0AL02087 | opensecrets = N00030768 | assets = martha-roby | legistorm = 2723/Rep_Martha_Roby_AL.html | followthemoney = | ontheissues = House/Martha_Roby